Dozens killed in Afghanistan court attack
A squad of heavily armed suicide attackers stormed a court building in western Afghanistan and triggered a day-long battle, taking hostages and leaving dozens dead or wounded.
Image 1 of 2	Damage at the site of an attack by Taliban suicide bombers Photo: Reuters	Image 1 of 2	Afghan security officials stand guard in Farah Photo: EPA	By Ben Farmer, Kabul
3:10PM BST 03 Apr 2013
Follow Officials said up to 53 people were killed and 91 injured in the attack on a government complex, which also housed a bank. The bulk of the dead were court clerks and civil servants who were taken hostage during the attack. Some were killed in their offices and others were herded into a basement and killed, he said. Nine men disguised in army uniform and driving military pick-up trucks approached the building in Farah province at around 8.30am. Two attackers quickly detonated their vests to try to clear a path inside and the others opened fire with assault rifles and rocket-propelled grenades. People at the site of the attack (Reuters)
The Taliban movement claimed responsibility for attack and said the fighters were trying to free insurgent prisoners scheduled for trial at the court. Fighting carried on throughout the day and the final two assailants managed to hold out until late afternoon. Related Articles
