“The Taliban took hostages from the court clerks and employees. When we finally got down to the basement, we found they had been killed.” No Nato troops were involved in the fighting, according to coalition headquarters in Kabul. Foreign troops have largely taken a back seat to Afghan troops in operations as they prepare to withdraw all combat forces by the end of next year. This summer is seen as a critical test of the strength of the Afghan forces. For the first time they will lead almost all operations and are already suffering high casualties. Around 200 policemen and soldiers died in March, when the traditional summer fighting season has yet to start in earnest. Farah borders both Iran and Helmand province and has seen security fall in recent months, police say partly because insurgents have been squeezed out of Helmand. Meanwhile, Asadullah Khalid, Afghanistan’s spy chief, returned to the country four months after he was critically wounded in his own guesthouse by a suicide bomber posing as a Taliban peace envoy. The scene of the attack (Reuters)
The would-be assassin detonated explosives hidden in his underpants as the two men met, leaving Mr Khalid with severe injuries. Mr Khalid, who has proven a ruthless opponent of both the Taliban and Pakistan’s support for the insurgents, has been treated in an American hospital since the December attack. A statement from the National Directorate of Security (NDS), said: “The enemies of peace and security attacked the director of the NDS in a strike that failed and he was taken for treatment first inside and then outside the country. “Finally after around four months of treatment, with the help of God, today at around 8.30 am, he returned home with good health.”
